      "content": "First, basic nitrogen atoms. Piperazine has two secondary amines (the nitrogens in the ring). However, in piperazine, the nitrogens are each bonded to two carbons and one hydrogen (so secondary amines). Wait, but in the SMILES, the piperazine is written as CN1CCN(...)CC1. Wait, the first N is connected to a methyl group (C), then the ring. Wait, maybe the piperazine is actually a 1-methylpiperazine? Let me check. The SMILES starts with CN1CCN... So the first atom is N1 connected to a methyl (C), then two carbons, then another N connected to the substituent (c2...), then two more carbons closing the ring. So the structure is 1-methylpiperazine. The two nitrogens in the piperazine ring: the first is a tertiary amine (connected to three carbons: methyl and two ring carbons), and the other nitrogen is a secondary amine (connected to two ring carbons and the substituent). Wait, the substituent is attached to the second nitrogen. So the substituent is on the N of the piperazine. So the piperazine has one tertiary amine (the methylated N) and one secondary amine (the other N connected to the substituent). But wait, in piperazine, each N is connected to two CH2 groups. If one N is methylated, then that N is tertiary (three carbons: methyl and two CH2 groups), and the other N is secondary (two CH2 groups and the substituent). So the molecule has a tertiary amine in the piperazine ring. Tertiary amines are structural alerts for CYP2D6 inhibition. That's a key point.",
