      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "Next, the substituent on the piperazine is a pyrimidine ring. The pyrimidine has a phenyl group and a trifluoromethyl group. The phenyl is an aromatic ring, contributing to lipophilicity. The trifluoromethyl group is highly lipophilic as well. The pyrimidine itself is a planar, aromatic heterocycle, which can contribute to stacking interactions. The presence of multiple aromatic rings (piperazine isn't aromatic, but the pyrimidine and phenyl are) increases lipophilicity. CYP2D6 substrates/inhibitors often have lipophilic aromatic rings, so this fits.",
